Static pods, how the control plane bootstraps itself.

A static pod is a pod the kube-let runs directly from a manifest on disk, without involving the ay-pee-eye server at all.

The kube-let watches a directory, by default slash e-t-c slash kubernetes slash manifests, for yaml files. Each file is a pod manifest. The kube-let reads the file, starts the pod, and then creates a mirror pod in the ay-pee-eye server so that kubectl get pods can see it. It keeps the pod alive, restarting it on crash, and watches the file for changes.

Here is the key behaviour. You cannot delete a static pod with kubectl. Deleting the mirror pod just removes it from the ay-pee-eye server's view, and the kube-let recreates the mirror within seconds. To actually stop a static pod, you move or delete its manifest file on the node.

Why does this exist. The control plane has a chicken and egg problem. How do you start the ay-pee-eye server when you need the ay-pee-eye server to start things. Static pods are the answer. On a kube-ay-dee-m control plane node, the manifests directory contains the manifests for et-see-dee, the ay-pee-eye server, the controller manager, and the scheduler. The kube-let starts on boot, reads those files, and brings up the control plane, et-see-dee first, then the ay-pee-eye server, then the rest. The control plane literally bootstraps itself from files on disk.

Static pods are useful outside the control plane too, for any node level agent that must run even when the ay-pee-eye server is unreachable, because they do not depend on it to start.
